  <title translate="true">Motion Derivative</title>
  <keywords>
    <keyword translate="true">Motion Derivative<keyword translate="true">Acceleration</keyword><keyword translate="true">First Motion Derivative</keyword><keyword translate="true">Second Motion Derivatve</keyword><keyword translate="true">Velocity</keyword><keyword translate="true">What is...</keyword></keyword>
  </keywords>
  <body>
    <para styleclass="Popup Box"><table styleclass="PopupTable" rowcount="1" colcount="1">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Popup Box-Elements" translate="true">Motion-Derivative</text><text styleclass="Interface" translate="true">:</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true"> the &apos;rate-of-change of a motion variable, usually with respect to time or machine angle&apos;. </text><text styleclass="Popup Box-Elements" translate="true">Motion-Derivatives</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true"> of Displacement are Velocity, Acceleration, and Jerk.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Popup Box-Elements" translate="true">Motion-derivatives</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true"> are derived symbolically (in MD), which means that a motion-value at a random machine angle is evaluated exactly.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">When </text><text styleclass="Popup Box-Elements" translate="true">motion-derivatives</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true"> are found numerically, a motion-value at a random machine angle is not evaluated, it is approximated.</text></para>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table></para>
